Package com.github.tommyettinger.tweenmachine

Class TweenEquations

java.lang.Object
com.github.tommyettinger.tweenmachine.TweenEquations
public final class TweenEquations extends Object
Provides predefined TweenEquation constants and ways to generate TweenFunction instances, as well as acting as the registry for known TweenEquation values so that they can be looked up by name. This has every Penner easing function. Unlike the original Universal Tween Engine, every easing function that has an IN and an OUT version now also has an INOUT and OUTIN version. The original didn't supply any OUTIN versions.
You can view the graphs for every TweenEquation here.

  • Field Details

    • REGISTRY

      public static final OrderedMap<String,TweenEquation> REGISTRY
      Maps String tag keys to TweenEquation values, storing them typically in insertion order. This is not intended for external use, but is public in case it is ever needed directly. You can also obtain the tags on their own using getTags(), or an Array with every TweenEquation using getTweenEquations().

    • linearFunction

      public static final TweenFunction linearFunction
      Linear interpolation; just returns its argument.

    • linear

      public static final TweenEquation linear
      Plain linear interpolation, or "lerp"; this just returns the alpha it is given.

    • smooth

      public static final TweenEquation smooth
      "Smoothstep" or a cubic Hermite spline.
      This has been modified slightly for numerical correctness. The form of this spline usually given, {code a * a * (3 - 2 * a)}, can exceed 1 for many inputs that are just less than 1, which makes that form much harder to use in a table lookup because an output larger than 1 could mean an out-of-bounds index. Instead, we use the form a * a * (1 - a - a + 2), which always stays in the range 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.

    • smoothOutIn

      public static final TweenEquation smoothOutIn
      "Smoothstep" or a cubic Hermite spline, but flipped.
      This has been modified slightly for numerical correctness. The form of this spline usually given, {code a * a * (3 - 2 * a)}, can exceed 1 for many inputs that are just less than 1, which makes that form much harder to use in a table lookup because an output larger than 1 could mean an out-of-bounds index. Instead, we use the form a * a * (1 - a - a + 2), which always stays in the range 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.

    • smooth2

      public static final TweenEquation smooth2
      "Smoothstep" or a cubic Hermite spline, applied twice.
      This has been modified slightly for numerical correctness. The form of the cubic Hermite spline usually given, {code a * a * (3 - 2 * a)}, can exceed 1 for many inputs that are just less than 1, which makes that form much harder to use in a table lookup because an output larger than 1 could mean an out-of-bounds index. Instead, we use the form a * a * (1 - a - a + 2), which always stays in the range 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.

    • smooth2OutIn

      public static final TweenEquation smooth2OutIn
      "Smoothstep" or a cubic Hermite spline, applied twice, but flipped.
      This has been modified slightly for numerical correctness. The form of the cubic Hermite spline usually given, {code a * a * (3 - 2 * a)}, can exceed 1 for many inputs that are just less than 1, which makes that form much harder to use in a table lookup because an output larger than 1 could mean an out-of-bounds index. Instead, we use the form a * a * (1 - a - a + 2), which always stays in the range 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.

    • smoother

      public static final TweenEquation smoother
      A quintic Hermite spline by Ken Perlin.
      This was modified slightly because the original constants were meant for doubles, and here we use floats. Without this tiny change (the smallest possible change here, from 10.0f to 9.999998f), giving an input of 0.99999994f, or one of thousands of other inputs, would unexpectedly produce an output greater than 1.0f .

    • smootherOutIn

      public static final TweenEquation smootherOutIn
      A quintic Hermite spline by Ken Perlin, but flipped.
      This was modified; see smoother.

    • fade

      public static final TweenEquation fade
      A quintic Hermite spline by Ken Perlin; this uses the same function as smoother.
      This was modified slightly because the original constants were meant for doubles, and here we use floats. Without this tiny change (the smallest possible change here, from 10.0f to 9.999998f), giving an input of 0.99999994f, or one of thousands of other inputs, would unexpectedly produce an output greater than 1.0f .

    • fadeOutIn

    • elasticOutIn

      public static final TweenEquation elasticOutIn
      Stays within the mid-range, using elastic with TweenFunction.flip() called on it. This should act like Elastic.INOUT in Universal Tween Engine, but with the start and end halves swapped and offset. This does not act like Interpolation.elastic in libGDX; use springOutIn for that.
      This will stay inside the 0-1 range for output.
      Base is 2, exponent is 10, scale is 1, intensity is 0.45.

    • get

      public static TweenEquation get(String tag)
      Looks up the given tag in a registry of TweenEquations, and if there exists one with that name, returns it. Otherwise, this returns null.
      Parameters:
      tag - a tag used to register a TweenEquation here
      Returns:
      the TweenEquation registered with the given tag, or null if none exists for that tag

    • getTags

      public static Array<String> getTags()
      Gets a direct reference to the tags used as keys for the TweenEquation registry. This Array can be sorted if you want, or otherwise rearranged. If new tags are registered, this will reflect those changes.
      Returns:
      an Array containing every String tag registered for a TweenEquation; direct reference

    • getTweenEquations

      public static Array<TweenEquation> getTweenEquations()
      Allocates a new Array of TweenEquation items, fills it with every registered TweenEquation, and returns that Array. This is not a direct reference; modifying the Array won't change the registered contents.
      Returns:
      a new Array containing every TweenEquation registered

    • powFunction

      public static TweenFunction powFunction(float power)
      Produces a TweenFunction that uses the given power variable. When power is greater than 1, this starts slowly, speeds up in the middle and slows down at the end. The rate of acceleration and deceleration changes based on the parameter. Noninteger parameters are supported, unlike the Pow in libGDX. Negative powers are not supported.
      The functions this method produces are not well-behaved when their a parameter is less than 0 or greater than 1.
      Returns:
      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

    • powOutInFunction

      The functions this method produces are not well-behaved when their a parameter is less than 0 or greater than 1.

      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

      public static TweenFunction kumaraswamyFunction(double a, double b)
      Produces a TweenFunction that uses the possible shapes of the Kumaraswamy distribution, but without involving a random component. This can produce a wide range of shapes for the interpolation, and may require generating several during development to get a particular shape you want. The a and b parameters must be greater than 0.0, but have no other requirements. Most curves that this method produces are somewhat asymmetrical.
      Parameters:
      a - the Kumaraswamy distribution's a parameter
      b - the Kumaraswamy distribution's b parameter
      Returns:
      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration
      See Also:
      • Wikipedia's page on this distribution.

    • biasGainFunction

      public static TweenFunction biasGainFunction(float shape, float turning)
      Produces an TweenFunction that uses the given shape and turning variables. A wrapper around TweenUtils.barronSpline(float, float, float) to use it as a TweenEquation or TweenFunction. Useful because it can imitate the wide variety of symmetrical equations by setting turning to 0.5 and shape to some value greater than 1, while also being able to produce the inverse of those equations by setting shape to some value between 0 and 1. It can also produce asymmetrical equations by using a turning value other than 0.5 . These asymmetrical equations can be useful because they can look like an INOUT or an OUTIN equation with one half larger than the other. Most IN or OUT equations start and end with different derivatives, but if shape is greater than 1, the derivative will approach 0 at both the start and end, as long as turning is in-between 0 and 1 (both exclusive). If turning is 0, this will look like an OUT function when shape is greater than 1. If turning is 1, this will look like an IN function when shape is greater than 1. In the case where shape is less than 1, these will be swapped.
      Parameters:
      shape - must be greater than or equal to 0; values greater than 1 are more like "INOUT" equations
      turning - a value between 0.0 and 1.0, inclusive, where the shape changes
      Returns:
      an TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

    • bounceFunction

      public static TweenFunction bounceFunction(float... pairs)
      Produces a TweenFunction that uses the given width, height, width, height, ... float array. Unlike bounceOutFunction(float...), this bounces at both the start and end of its interpolation. Fair warning; using this is atypically complicated, and you should generally stick to using a predefined TweenEquation, such as bounce4. You can also hand-edit the values in pairs; if you do, every even index is a width, and every odd index is a height. Later widths are no greater than earlier ones; this is also true for heights. No width is typically greater than 1.5f, and they are always positive and less than 2f.
      Parameters:
      pairs - width, height, width, height... in pairs; typically none are larger than 1.5f, and all are positive
      Returns:
      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

    • swingFunction

      public static TweenFunction swingFunction(float scale)
      Produces a TweenFunction that uses the given scale variable. This drops below 0.0 at the start of the range, accelerates very rapidly, exceeds 1.0 at the middle of the input range, and ends returning 1.0. Negative parameters are not supported.
      This will typically go outside the 0-1 range for output.
      The functions this method produces are not well-behaved when their a parameter is less than 0 or greater than 1.
      Returns:
      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

    • springFunction

      public static TweenFunction springFunction(float value, float power, int bounces, float scale)
      Produces a TweenFunction that uses the given value, power, bounces, and scale variables. This drops below 0.0 near the middle of the range, accelerates near-instantly, exceeds 1.0 just after that, and ends returning 1.0. Negative parameters are not supported.
      This will typically go outside the 0-1 range for output.
      The functions this method produces are not well-behaved when their a parameter is less than 0 or greater than 1. This acts like com.badlogic.gdx.math.Interpolation.elastic rather than a Penner easing function.
      Returns:
      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

    • springOutInFunction

      public static TweenFunction springOutInFunction(float value, float power, int bounces, float scale)
      Produces a TweenFunction that uses the given value, power, bounces, and scale variables. This accelerates near-instantly, wiggles in to settle near the middle of the range, accelerates again near the end, and finishes returning 1.0. Negative parameters are not supported.
      This will typically stay inside the 0-1 range for output, unless value is much less than 2, power is much less than 10, or scale is much larger than 1.
      The functions this method produces are not well-behaved when their a parameter is less than 0 or greater than 1.
      Returns:
      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration

      a TweenFunction that will use the given configuration
